recordings.file-name: XC193899-Woodpigeon snoring sounds, Broad Meadow, County Antrim 2014-03-014 0926hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: Woodpigeons are deep voiced. Their vocabulary is quite limited, although they produce sound to advertise display by wing flapping, as well as using vocals. Apart from deep sonorous cooing (listen to XC193757, XC193878 and XC193888) they also utter random 'snoring' sounds (although the bird is far from asleep). The first snore comes just after 0:03. Often the snoring carries on intermittently for minutes on end but in a totally ad hoc manner. Minutes may pass with no calls whatsoever. The gaps between snores in this recording are in real time; the recording has not been edited. At one point (0:47) a snoring note becomes the first note in a song stanza. Other birds fill the background and consist of Little Grebe (samples at 0:01 and clearly at 0:54), as well as several broadcasts from Blue Tit (such as two seconds from 0:02), Great Tit from 0:08, Wren 0:12, Coal Tit 0:18 (for under two seconds), Magpie and Dunnock (0:57 to end).

recordings.file-name: XC193889-Woodpigeon wing clap, Crawfordsburn, County Down 2014-07-06 0653hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: This recording starts with the opening (4 note) stanza of Woodpigeon coos but the bird then stops short and flies away (it quits after delivering the first note in the next verse). Listen to XC193757, XC193878 and XC193888 for full calling sequences. Woodpigeons are noisy in flight but fliers that are not startled make much less noise and may not generate wing claps. This bird was disturbed - presumably by my presence. At other times wing claps are used during display.

Typical Woodpigeon broadcast, consisting of four notes in first stanza but five in all others - except the last, that comprises a solitary note. For more detailed discussion, see XC193878 and XC193757. The interest in this recording is the example of the bird slowing down in part of the 5-noted stanzas, such as just after 0:03 and 0:06. This is not unusual and individuals can also add more oomph to certain notes or, when more than one bird is heard calling, there is often a difference in the global pitch of all utterances - as if one is closer to a baritone voice. Overall, Woodpigeon has one of the deepest voices - if not the deepest - of all birds that vocalise in Ireland.

Classic call from a Woodpigeon. The introductory stanza consists of four notes. Subsequent phrases consist of five notes. When you listen to the quality of the individual notes, it seems the extra note that is inserted to create a series of five notes is THE SECOND NOTE in the five-note stanza. By listening again to the four-note opening stanza, it can be established that the 'novel' note is missing. Although not especially emphasised in this recording, many Woodpigeons exaggerate the 'novel note' in their delivery. Often the bird raises its voice at this point. In other ways, this recording is typical: an opening salvo of 4 notes, followed by two sets of 5 notes (generally two or three sets of 5 notes are broadcast), followed by a single, solo note that can be thought of as a full stop. This final single note also has a fairly distinctive character and rises slightly in pitch. Two Woodpigeons that call back and forth can be heard at XC193757. One of these employs a longer series of 5 notes in its broadcast, although it conforms to the standard pattern of beginning with four notes and then concluding with a single note. 

Woodpigeons can be heard from January to late August (sometimes later in autumn too). Apart from the - let's call it - social cooing, their vocabulary is limited. Deep groans can sometimes be heard (XC193899) and, of course, the species employs wing-claps as part of its display. By listening a lot to Woodpigeons (in Northern Ireland) throughout 2013 and 2014, a remarkable difference in the timing of calling became clear. Both winters were mild but in 2013 almost no Woodpigeons called until the second half of March (and only infrequently during late March). The 2013 breeding season was remarkably poor in all countryside that I regularly visit. For example, I saw just one young Woodpigeon in my garden (where Woodpigeons are present throughout the year). As a result of the low productivity and late commencement of calling in 2013, it was immediately clear that a change in calling schedules affected 2014. Birds began calling regularly in mid January and a busy level of calling was maintained right through February and March. Amazingly, I then saw youngsters in early April and breeding continued right though until early September (as I write). Whatever triggered the good breeding season (and winter weather may not have been a direct factor, except if the mild winter of 2012-2013 might have influenced activity in 2013-14 if the population had enjoyed a boom in numbers from the first mild winter?) the upshot was that early calling also signalled early breeding. Of course, more detailed monitoring may show that all of these things are run-of-the-mill in the ways of the Woodpigeon!

recordings.loc: Strickland's Glen, North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
Two Woodpigeons taking turns to call - a typical scenario. I do not have an explanation that favours neighbours calling to each other (either of the same or opposite sex) or territorial rights being broadcast or perhaps a pair hailing each other. Sociability may be closest to the truth. One reference tends to support this contention. In A STUDY OF BIRD SONG (second enlarged edition, 1973) by Edward A Armstrong, the following comment appears in Addenda 1 (page257): 'When shooting woodpigeons, French wildfowlers imitate their cooing to reassure perched birds (R.G.Busnel and J.Giban; Colloque 1958).' Hence, my best guess is that any Woodpigeons in an area like to keep within earshot of each other. For example, a walk along linear woodland - such as a lakeshore - will encounter a corridor of Woodpigeon sound. As in this recording, rules of etiquette apply. Just like debaters, each waits for the other to finish before 'returning fire'. 

There is a standard pattern in Woodpigeon voice. The opening stanza (almost) invariably consists of four notes. All subsequent stanzas contain five notes. A full burst usually has the four-note opening followed by 2, 3 or 4 repetitions of the five-noted stanza.  At the end of the broadcast a final solo note signifies a kind of aural full stop. The full stop is optional and is sometimes not produced. The two birds in this recording are pretty standard. However, the first caller is unusual in that as many as 6 five-noted stanzas are uttered. Perhaps the responses from the second bird encouraged the first to produce more five-noted stanzas than usual? The first bird begins with four notes, then delivers a series of 6 five-noted stanzas and 'signs off' with a full stop just after 0:21. At 0:26 the second bird commences. Again, its first stanza contains four notes, followed by 3 five-noted stanzas. Finally, just after 0:36, it produces a full stop. Less than a second later - just after 0:37 - the original bird sets off on a repeat of its first performance. Note how the mood of delivery can vary over each five-noted stanza. For example, some stanzas are more energetic whereas others sound lazy or sleepy. Background species include song bursts from (in chronological order) Chaffinch (such as at 0:00 and 0:22), Blackbird, Goldfinch and Wren.

Bird, presumably the male (bill color brighter and breast more rosy than the second bird) sitting on nest in ivy, on trunk of Field Maple. Bird sitting flat on nest, frequently pecking downwards into nesting material and constantly twitching its wings. Rhythmic shuffle of  primaries can be heard especially in the beginning of the recording,Nearby presumed female harvesting ivy-berries and in between looking at the scene. Male sometimes slightly changing position on nest. Birds seen. Calling and pecking-wing twitching behaviour went on for about 15 minutes.
